The losers remain challengers.
HARARE: Before this month's presidential elections, I was convinced that irregularities in the elections could have serious consequences for Zimbabwe itself and for southern Africa as a whole.
Despite the shadows of war and terrorism, I called for fair and free elections.
The people of Zimbabwe have not received them.
Instead, they have received terror.
In the two years leading up to the presidential elections, the people of Zimbabwe were victims of intimidation, harassment, and threats by the party of Robert Mugabe, the Zimbabwe African National Union – Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF), whose program is one of state-subsidized terrorism.
The ZANU terrorism is attributed to the thugs among the veterans from Zimbabwe's independence war two decades ago, the government militias, and young men, all of whom are supported by the police.
The sequence of intimidation and violence resulted in my party, the Movement for Democratic Change (MDC), not reaching the electorate in many areas, particularly the rural regions.
Moreover, the government of my opponent, President Mugabe, effectively disenfranchised hundreds of thousands of voters in the cities, particularly in the capital Harare and in Chitungwiza.
Because there were not enough polling stations overall, in my opinion, more than 360,000 people had to stand in line alone in Harare and Chitungwiza and were not able to cast their ballot.
I still doubt the legitimacy of the election results because Mugabe's militias prevented MDC observers from being present at 52% of rural polling stations.
By the end of the voting, our party lacked observers at 6 out of 10 polling stations in the countryside.
This means that Mugabe's supporters were able to enforce their will in these polling stations.
We are compiling a comprehensive list of all the polling stations that were controlled only by ZANU supporters.
In our previous investigations, even at this early stage, a pattern has emerged: in these polling stations, most votes were cast for Mugabe.
Given the overwhelming evidence, I cannot accept the result of the presidential elections, in which the incumbent president Robert Mugabe emerged as the winner with 56% of the 3 million votes cast.
The official result does not reflect the true will of Zimbabwe's people and is deemed illegitimate by them.
The people of Zimbabwe were brought to realize their right to freely and democratically elect a president of their choice.
The fight over the election results is a political matter that must be resolved politically.
Food and fuel are scarce, jobs are being lost, and inflation is over 100%.
The people of Zimbabwe were brave and determined, and they deserve to have this acknowledged.
Maybe it's not too late for that.
I write this text in sorrow, for Mugabe's regime still disregards the will of the people.
Whatever may happen, I will stand as a faithful servant by the side of the people and go the distance with them.
The English translation of the given German sentence is: "Perhaps the government wants to arrest me."
I was also arrested for high treason before the elections.
In the worst case, they even want to kill me.
But the government will never be able to break the will of the people to reclaim their rights and power.
It lies in our hands to effect a democratic transformation.
In the coming days, we will experience moments of fear, but we must not allow despair to overcome us.
The political change is unstoppable.
But we must be ready to pay a high price for our freedom.
President Mugabe and his henchmen fear the people, and we have heard that they will do everything in their power to kill the messenger.
If it comes to that, I only ask the people of Zimbabwe to remain strong and see through what we have begun together.
There are many heroes in the people of Zimbabwe - heroes who waited for hours to vote, heroes who were not driven away.
It are the heroes of a new Zimbabwe whose voices must be heard in the world.
We have walked together along a very rocky path in order to bring about a democratic transformation in our country.
In the history of mankind, a people have rarely had to endure such violence and still managed to preserve kindness and exuberance.
I notice that the population of Zimbabwe is impatient.
I understand that.
But for there to be a political process, they must be patient and wait.
You cannot simply let these elections stand, but you must also not fall for Mugabe's provocation and resort to violence.
The people of Zimbabwe want the change, in the constitution, in the legal system, legitimate change, and they will achieve it, despite all obstacles.
We know that we are not alone.
We know that voting fraud occurs throughout Africa.
In most African countries, irregularities, fraud, and deceit seem to be standard in elections.
In Africa, there is always some kind of crisis concerning elections somewhere.
It is sad, but the entire continent is afflicted with governments that resort to dishonest means when it comes to granting people their right to vote.
But those who want something else can hope.
The fight of Zimbabwe is not yet over.
There is still time to draw lessons for Africa and the world from our experience.
My people are in the hour of their greatest need.
I pledge not to leave it.
